observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management require the:

Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of the local road networks, prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Networks and furnish the Municipal Accountant and GSO-Designate a copy thereof for reconciliation of their records;

GSO – Designate to prepare the Report on Local Road Networks, maintain local road inventory, road map and property cards for all roads and its components;

Municipal Accountant to include disclosures on the total Road Networks account in the NTFS following the format provided in the Circular; and

Municipal Engineer to provide a complete description and cost segregation of each road component for road projects.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
Conduct a comprehensive review to identify and confirm the existence of dormant accounts in the books of the Municipality;
Prepare and submit a request for write-off as soon as all relevant provisions of the Circular, particularly those pertaining to the proper disposition and derecognition of dormant accounts, are duly complied and implemented.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Acting Municipal Treasurer to:
Issue a revenue circular for the submission of certified ITRs address to all businesses in the Municipality to ensure that a comparison between the sworn statement of gross receipts or sales and the certified ITRs be carried out to ascertain deficiencies that may be uncovered therein;
Initiate the conduct of examination of the books of businesses to assess any tax deficiencies that may be discovered, in case of non-submission of certified ITRs of businesses at the reglementary date of April 30 of each year or for whatever legal grounds they may deem appropriate;
Fast-tract the submission of the revised Revenue Code of the Municipality to help bring to fruition of a more prosperous and self-sustaining Municipality; and
Issue demand letters addressed to these contractors requiring them to settle the accrued business taxes for CY 2023 that should have been collected during CY 2024 by the Municipality;
Direct the Acting Municipal Treasurer, in coordination with the BPLO, to cause the alignment of the process and requirements on Business Registration with the Local Revenue Code by discontinuing the practice of examining the books of accounts of business taxpayers for business registration purposes without prior authority to do so;
Require the Municipal Accountant to draw appropriate receivable and revenue entries for the collectible amounts from said contractors for CY 2024 books of accounts and every year thereafter; and
Require the Acting Municipal Treasurer, in coordination with the Municipal Accountant, to seek legislative authority to develop and implement a business tax withholding and collection system/policy that will authorize the Municipality to withhold amounts from current year’s income payments to long-term contractors not registered in the Municipality as an alternative means to settle their back taxes of previous years or to incorporate said provisions in the proposed revised Revenue Code of the Municipality.

We recommended that Management direct the:

GSO-Designate / Appraisal Committee Head with the Inspectorate Team to:
Inspect the said donated PPEs except for infrastructure projects;
Appraise the donated properties with no declared values to determine the acquisition cost of the said properties as of the date of donation; and
Issue appropriate accountability records such as PAR and/or ICS and update Property Cards relative to the donated PPEs.

Municipal Environment and Natural Resources Officer (MENRO) to provide copies of MOA and Deeds of Donation relative to the donated properties from the Department of Environment and Natural Resources (DENR) – Environmental Management Bureau (EMB), Region 1 to the Municipal Accountant and GSO-Designate for recording and issuance of appropriate property forms;

Municipal Social Welfare and Development Officer (MSWDO) to provide copies of document/s substantiating the receipt of desktop computer from the Provincial Government of Pangasinan to the Municipal Accountant and GSO-Designate for recording and issuance of appropriate property forms;

Municipal Engineer to provide copies of documents relative to the inspection report and acceptance of the donated one-story Diagnostic and Animal Bite Treatment Center to the Municipal Accountant and GSO-Designate for recording; and

Waterworks Superintendent to submit to the Municipal Accountant and GSO-Designate, copy furnished the Audit Team, detailed list of quantity of donated goods/materials such as HDPE, PVC Pipes, and fittings received from ERAMEN Minerals Inc. relative to the Expansion of Potable Water Lines of IWWS. Likewise, submit to the Municipal Accountant and GSO-Designate, copy furnished the Audit Team, inventory of the said donated pipes and/or materials as of December 31, 2022 to determine whether these were already used in the aforesaid expansion project or remained in the custody of his office for proper recording in the accounting and property records.

Municipal Accountant to:

Record in the books of accounts the receipt and issuance of donated properties based on the Deeds of Donation, SB Resolutions, MOA, PARs and/or ICS, Appraisal Report from the Appraisal Committee, Inspection Report from the Municipal Engineer (infrastructure assets) and inventory reports relative to the donated pipes/materials for the Expansion of Potable Water Lines of Infanta Water Works System project of the LGU;

To verify the date of receipt and/or completion of donated PPEs and recognize depreciation thereon; and

Update the PPE Ledger Cards relative to the donated PPEs

We recommended that Management:

Submit to the Audit Team a Management Representation Letter within 60 days from the effectivity of COA Circular No. 2021-014 and every March 31 thereafter to ensure that the LGU has designed, implemented and reviewed its internal controls and procedures over the use of e-payment systems;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Ensure that all online disbursements are supported with duly approved disbursement vouchers which would invariably bear the signature of proper officials;

Submit for audit the DVs for all online disbursements made for CY 2022;

Prepare an electronic disbursements journal to record all e-payments made by the LGU; and

Require the Municipal Treasurer to prepare a Report of ADA Issued and Daily Report of e-Payments from Agency Account to record all ADA issued and e-Payments made daily.

We recommended that Management direct the MDRRMO to:

Stop charging unrelated expenses or expenses not directly related to the LDRRMF to ensure strict compliance in the proper utilization of the LDRRMF;

Ensure that the PPAs included in the LDRRMFIP were directly related to DRRM purposes;

Inform the MDRRM Council regarding the need of insurance coverage for the municipal evacuation center through GSIS;

Seek the approval of the SB through the passage of SB Resolution relative to the provision of appropriation for the insurance coverage of the evacuation center; and

Submit monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF before the 15th day after the end of each month through the MDRRMC and MDC to the Audit Team.

Likewise, we recommended that Management instruct the Municipal Accountant to:

Prepare monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF; and

Observe judicious preparation of quarterly utilization report of LDRRMF to ensure completeness and accurate reporting of transactions thereof in the Full Disclosure Policy Portal of the DILG.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Treasurer to:

Observe the submission of RAAFs and CRAAF within the required period;

Direct her personnel with accountabilities for accountable forms to meticulously prepare RAAFs to avoid errors and ensure that the necessary information such as the date of preparation and control numbers for each RAAF are properly indicated;

Judiciously review the RAAFs and CRAAF to ensure its accuracy and completeness before approving and submitting the same to the Audit Team; and

Require the accountable officer in charge in the issuance of cash tickets to prepare his RAAF to be consolidated in CRAAF.

We recommended that Management require the:
Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of the local road networks, prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Networks and furnish the Municipal Accountant and GSO-Designate a copy thereof for reconciliation of their records;
GSO – Designate to prepare the Report on Local Road Networks, maintain local road inventory, road map and property cards for all roads and its components;
Municipal Accountant to include disclosures on the total Road Networks account in the NTFS following the format provided in the Circular; and
Municipal Engineer to provide a complete description and cost segregation of each road component for road projects.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Engineer to:

Require the grant of contract time extensions and suspension of works only when supported with proofs to back-up the reasons for such or claims by the contractor;

Instruct all inspectors to prepare monitoring and/or inspection reports for every site inspection duly documented with visual evidences;

Prepare Contract Time Extensions and Suspension of Work Orders in accordance with RA No. 9184;

Adjust the contract duration to consider holidays and weekends during the detailed engineering activities of the LGU for efficient implementation of infrastructure projects;

Submit to the Audit Team copies of Contract Time Extensions and Suspension Work Orders issued including the supporting documents to substantiate the same; and

Reflect in the Quarterly Report of GPPA the revised contracted completion date indicating the number of days covered with an approved contract time extension and/or suspension order.

Strictly monitor and inspect all completed projects during the one-year defects liability period to determine any defects for correction by the concerned contractors;

Observe the issuance CFA after one year from project completion date;

Require the concerned contractor to post the required warranty security before the issuance of CFA; and

Furnish the Audit Team copies of issued CFA and proofs that the contractor posted the required warranty security.

We recommended that Management:

a. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to maintain complete Supplies Ledger Cards for each item of supplies and materials of the inventory; 

b. Instruct the GSO-Designate to maintain complete stock cards for each item of supplies and materials of inventory; 

c. Require the GSO – Designate to consolidate the Requisition Issue Slip issued and prepare Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued which shall serve as the basis of the Municipal Accountant in recording the issued supplies as expense; 

d. Consider the creation of Inventory Committee to assist the GSO-Designate in the inventory-taking process; 

e. Instruct the GSO – Designate/Inventory Committee to conduct periodic physical inventory of unissued supplies and materials at least once a year and report in the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) to be reconciled with the accounting records; 

f. Require the GSO – Designate to issue Inventory Custodian Slips (ICS) to inventories/supplies considered as small tangible items with estimated service life of more than one year to establish accountability over them; and 

g. Provide stockroom for the use of General Service Office to store the supplies and materials purchased including equipment which are to be issued to the office/department needing the same.

We recommended that Management:

a. Create an inventory committee that will primarily handle the inventory of local road network system using the Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network System; 

b. Require the GSO-Designate, in coordination with the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Engineer, to reconcile the inventory of local roads and road maps with the recorded road networks in the books of accounts; 

c. Require the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and GSO-Designate with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects, taking also into account the allocation of the cost incurred for consolidated road projects based on the Program of Works; 

d. Require the GSO-Designate to prepare a Report of Local Road Network at the end of each accounting period; 

e. Require the GSO-Designate to prepare and maintain complete Local Road Network Property Cards; 

f. Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain complete Local Road Network Property Cards; and 

g. Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare lapsing schedule for the computation of depreciation cost for each component of Road Network and to provide note disclosure on the Road Network System of the LGU in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We recommended that Management:

a. Require the Municipal Accountant to impose to the Supplier the liquidated damages amounting to ₱39,595.50 due to the incurrence of delay of six calendar days in the delivery of sacks of commercial rice. Also, require the said supplier to submit the OR on the payment of the said purchase; 

b. Require the Municipal Treasurer to issue OR upon receipt of payment of liquidated damages by the Supplier; 

c. Require the Municipal Accountant to submit to the Audit Team the OR relative to the payment of procured 2,933 sacks of rice; 

d. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all procurements of goods are supported with Delivery Receipts, and duly accomplished Acceptance and Inspection Report (AIR) showing the date of acceptance and inspection to validate prompt delivery; 

e. Require the BAC Secretariat to update the form used in gathering the lowest calculated and responsive quotation for all transactions involving procurement undertaken through alternative methods to indicate the other terms and conditions of the contract; and 

f. Instruct the BAC Secretariat to ensure that the delivery period/terms in the approved PO are the same with the postings in the PhilGEPS to ensure transparency in all procurement of the Agency and that the RFQs, as a formal letter from the agency, are signed by the BAC Chairman.

We recommended that Management instruct the MENRO-Designate to:

a. Strictly implement the no segregation, no collection policy of the LGU and imposed the charging of fines and penalties against the persons committing prohibited acts in waste segregation and disposal and the like; 

b. Reassess the current situation in the sanitary landfill and take immediate action on the deficiencies noted particularly with the minimum requirements/considerations in the operation of the sanitary landfill in conformity with Sections 1 and 2, Rule XIV of DENR AO No. 2001-34 dated December 20, 2001; 

c. Conduct trainings for the drivers, helpers and segregators and other personnel involved in the operation of sanitary landfill relative to site operation and maintenance, hazardous materials recognition and screening and heavy equipment operations, with emphasis on safety, health, environment controls and emergency procedures. Also, include in the trainings the importance of wearing and using appropriate safety equipment; and 

d. Facilitate the necessary revisions on the 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan of the LGU required by the NSWMC in order to secure the approval and immediate implementation of the same.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Engineer to conduct inspection to validate the status of those infrastructure projects that were identified by the Municipal Accountant based on the available accounting records;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Coordinate with the Municipal Engineer to determine the date of completion of those infrastructure assets already identified in the records for reclassification thereof;
Provide depreciation costs after reclassification of the completed projects in order to present fairly the Accumulated Depreciation and Government Equity accounts in the financial statements;
Maintain subsidiary ledgers for CIP accounts to facilitate determination and identification of the projects recorded thereto; and
Recognize the Gravelling of Access Main Road at Covered Landfill at Barangay Bamban recorded as CIP-Infrastructure Assets account as Prior Period Adjustment to Government Equity account upon retrieval of documents pertaining to the said project;
The proposed adjusting journal entry is presented below.
Prior Period Adjustment		319,074.00
CIP-Infrastructure Assets			319,074.00
Instruct the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Engineer to exert utmost effort to locate the documents/records to identify the projects that were recorded in the books under CIP-Buildings and Other Structures account prior to CY 2018 with an aggregate cost of ₱45,553,008.08; and
To enjoin the Municipal Engineer, OIC-MBO, Municipal Treasurer and the BAC in identifying the projects recorded in CIP-Buildings and Other Structures account including their status, cost, location and date of completion.

We recommended that Management:
Create an Inventory Committee who will spearhead the conduct of the required physical count of all properties of the LGU and the preparation of the RPCPPE;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain complete SL for each group of PPEs and prepare and maintain lapsing schedule in the computation of depreciation of PPE accounts;
Instruct the GSO-Designate to prepare and maintain complete property cards; and
Require the Municipal Accountant and GSO-Designate as well as other concern officials to review and study the guidelines and procedures of COA Circular No. 2020-006 relative to the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances to assist the LGU in coming up with reliable PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

Management was amenable to the audit recommendations and had assured the Audit Team that they will work on the creation of the required Inventory Committee who will spearhead the conduct of the required physical count of all properties of the LGU and the preparation of RPCPPE. The Municipal Accountant agreed to the audit recommendations and committed to do his best in maintaining complete property ledger cards and preparing the lapsing schedule in the computation of depreciation of PPEs. Likewise, in her letter-reply, the GSO-Designate informed that she is already maintaining the required property cards for PPEs except for those properties that were already existing in the books since she assumed her office and those properties with no available records and unknown location. Moreover, the Municipal Accountant and GSO-Designate committed to review and study the guidelines and procedures of COA Circular No. 2020-006 relative to the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances to assist them in coming up with a more reliable PPE balance.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the TWG and BAC to thoroughly verify and validate the accuracy of the NFCC and the SLCC duly supported with Certificate of Final Acceptance and/or CPES Final Rating including the other eligibility requirements submitted by the bidders in order to ensure that the government contracts are awarded to qualified bidders;
Direct the BAC to ensure that winning bidders comply with the required posting of surety bonds callable upon demand as performance and warranty security duly certified by the Insurance Commission before the awarding and signing of the contract;
Require the Municipal Engineer to require the contractor to post warranty security that will address the structural defects that may be discovered from the final acceptance of the project up to the period prescribed in Section 62.2.3.2 of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA. 9184;
Instruct the Municipal Engineer to furnish the Audit Team copies of Certificate of Final Acceptance for completed contracts to monitor the posting of said warranty security by the contractors; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to release the retention money being withheld from the payment of procured non-expendable supplies after the lapse of the required warranty period of one (1) year.
Management was amenable to the audit observations and had expressed their willingness to comply with all the audit recommendations as stated in the letter reply of the BAC, Municipal Engineer and Municipal Accountant.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all disbursements are duly supported with complete documentation before approving the DVs;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to require the MHO, the LDRRMO and or the requisitioning officer to verify and certify that the drugs and medicines being procured fall within and conform with the latest edition of PNF Manual;
Require the Municipal Accountant in coordination with the Municipal Engineer to submit all the lacking documents relative to the payments on infrastructure projects for further verification and evaluation; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all the documentary requirements on progress and final payments relative to the implementation of infrastructure projects are complete before approving the DVs.
The Municipal Accountant was amenable to the audit observations and informed the Audit Team in his letter-reply that he has already coordinated with the OIC-Municipal Engineer to provide the lacking documentary requirements on the payments of infrastructure projects. Likewise, he assured the Audit Team that he will ensure that all the documentary requirements on progress and final payments relative to the implementation of infrastructure projects are complete before approving the DVs.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the LYDO and/or assigned official to review the executed MOA with ERAMEN Minerals Inc., and comply with the provisions thereof to ensure effective and efficient implementation and the attainment of the agreed goals of the CSR program;
Reorganize the LGU’s MDC and make them participate in the creation and/or formulation of subsequent project proposals in line with the CSR project of ERAMEN Minerals Inc. pursuant to the provisions in the MOA;
Require the LYDO and/or assigned official to ensure that all project proposals in line with the CSR project of ERAMEN Minerals, Inc. shall be approved by the SB through issuance of SB Resolutions;
Issue a formal office order or executive order to establish the Selection Team/Committee identifying its members, term of office and duties and responsibilities; and
Require the MSWDO to formulate written guidelines and policies on the grant of scholarship assistance to ensure equitable grant of the scholarship assistance.
Management assured the Audit Team to take appropriate actions in compliance with the audit recommendations. Likewise, the MSWDO had submitted the newly approved written guidelines and policies of LGU in the grant of scholarship assistance under the CSR Program for review and evaluation of the Audit Team.

We recommended that Management:

a. Require the GSO-Designate to ensure that the procurement of mobile phones is within the bounds of propriety and stop the procurement of luxurious phones intended for communication purposes only; 

b. Limit the issuance of mobile phone to one phone for each qualified official to Division Chief Rank or higher in rank. Unless justified, require the return of mobile phones in excess of the number required in the conduct of duty; 

c. Instruct the GSO-Designate to prepare PAR with complete details indicating the date of acquisition and the acquisition cost of the property issued duly signed by the Accountable Officer indicating the date in the receipt portion thereof; 

d. Require the GSO – Designate to ensure that all outgoing officials or retired LGU employees be required to return government properties issued to them before issuing clearance from property accountability; and 

e. Instruct the General Services Office-Designate to require the former employees to show proof that they have returned the mobile phones previously issued to them.

We recommended that Management:

a. Require the drivers to properly accomplish the trip tickets indicating all the necessary information for the control and monitoring of fuel consumption. 

b. Require the GSO-Designate to use the Requisition and Issue Voucher (RIV) form in all fuel requisition and issuance of fuel transactions; 

c. Require the GSO-Designate to inform and instruct the gasoline station to indicate in the individual invoices, the plate number of the vehicle requesting fuel; 

d. Instruct the GSO-Designate to prepare Daily Gas Issue Record, Summary of Requisition and Issue Voucher, Monthly Report of Official Travels and Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption; and 

e. For vehicles and heavy equipment with defective fuel gauge, require the GSO-Designate to undertake immediately the repair thereof, and shall henceforth, ensure to hold the drivers responsible for not reporting defective fuel gauge.

